News24 CorrespondentScience and Technology Minister Naledi Pandor. (File: Nasief Manie) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Johannesburg - A focus on the need for training colleges for budding farmers, nurses and teachers was highlighted by the ANC NEC subcommittee on Education and Health on Sunday. &nbsp;&ldquo;The [higher education and training] sector further recommends that the ANC ensure that the sector accelerates and completes the opening of professional colleges to increase training in agriculture, nursing, and teaching,&rdquo; said Naledi Pandor, chairperson of the national executive committee's subcommittee, in a statement about the party&rsquo;s ANC policy discussion document. &nbsp;The policy discussions come ahead of the ruling party&rsquo;s national policy conference in June.Between 1994 and 2000 the government shut down teacher training colleges and merged them with other institutions. &nbsp;In 2013, Minister of Higher Education Blade Nzimande announced plans to re-introduce teacher training colleges. &nbsp;In Sunday&rsquo;s media statement, the party also called for a model to be implemented by 2020 that would provide for free higher education for poor families &ndash; as well as increased support for families struggling to afford fees.&nbsp; &nbsp;Among other recommendations for the sector, the party wanted the finalisation of a framework for regulating higher education fees as well as the redesign for how funding was applied. &nbsp;The subcommittee also wanted the sector to &ldquo;put in place policies to facilitate an increase in retirement age of academic staff&rdquo;.Turning to health, the party raised concern that despite interventions such as certain genetic testing programmes, TB remained a &ldquo;primary underlying cause of death&rdquo; in SA.Nevertheless, it noted that the sector had performed well in terms of its HIV/ AIDS programmes. &nbsp;The party welcomed public submissions on its various policy discussions. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.